# OOB-First Principle — {Agent Name}

## Decision tree (applied per requirement)

```
Can the requirement be met by:

  1. Out of the Box capability?     →  Use OOB.       Fitment: "Out of the Box"
  2. Configuration (declarative)?    →  Use Config.    Fitment: "Configuration"
  3. Customisation (custom code)?    →  Customise.     Fitment: "Customization"

For each step, document the OOB / Config option you considered and rejected
(if you skipped to a lower level). The rationale lives in §8.2 OOB-first Decision Log
of the FDD.
```

## Project-level overrides

`projects/{p}/project.config.yaml oobOverrides.*` can steer the default at the platform level:

| Override key | Effect |
|---|---|
| `businessRules: prefer-js` | Prefer JavaScript over business rules when both could meet the requirement |
| `businessRules: prefer-business-rule` | Prefer business rules (the platform default) |
| `complexPlugin: prefer-azure-function` | Push complex CE plugins to Azure Functions (offloads compute, simplifies CE-side deployment) |
| `complexPlugin: prefer-plugin` | Keep complex logic as a CE plugin |

## Platform-specific OOB inventory

If this platform has a known OOB capability catalog (e.g., CE's first-party apps, F&O's localisation packs, Power BI's content packs), enumerate the categories here so reviewers know what "OOB" actually covers.

## OOB-first decision log

Every spec → plan handoff records the OOB-first decision per requirement in §8.2 of the FDD. The log is reviewed at `/clarify` time; if the decision changes, the log is updated and the rationale captured.
